\frac{W}{S} &= \frac{2(2n-1)(n-1)!}{(2n-1)!} = \frac{2(n-1)!}{(2n-2)!} \\
&= \frac{(n-1)!^2}{(n-1)!(n-2)!(n-1)!(n-2)!\cdots 2!1!} \\
&= \frac{(n-1)!}{(n-2)!}
\end{align*}
We see that if we increase $n$ from 500 to 501, $\frac{W}{S}$ increases, so $a_n = 500$.

Case 2: $a_n \ge 500$ ($n \le 30$): In this case, we can count $S$ with $x_i \ge 0$:
$$\sum_{x_{i} \ge 0} \frac{(2n-1)!}{x_0! x_1! x_2! \cdots x_{n-1}!}$$Since $x_i$ is 0 for $n-1 \le i \le 2n - 2$, we reduce all the above cases and get
$$\frac{(2n-1)!}{x_0! x_1! x_2!} \cdots x_{n-1}!$$In this case, we can count $W$ the same way as before:
$$d_{m, a} = \binom{a}{1} + \binom{a}{2} + \binom{a}{3} + \cdots + \binom{a}{a}$$Thus,
\begin{align*}
\frac{W}{S} &= \frac{d_{n-1, 1} + d_n, 2}{(2n-1)!/x_0! x_1! x_2! \cdots x_{n-1}!}\\
&\le \frac{2 \cdot d_{n-1, 1}}{(2n-1)!/x_0! x_1! x_2! \cdots x_{n-1}!}\\
&= \frac{2(n-1)!}{(2n-1)!}\\
&= \frac{2}{(2n-1)(2n-2)}
\end{align*}
By the way, if you add 1 to the value of $n$, the numerator becomes larger, so $a_n = \boxed{500}$.

