Let the sum $\sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(6+239k)^{717}$ be denoted as S.  Note that $6+239k=239k-233$. Then $S$ can be written as:

\begin{align*}
S = \sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(6+239k)^{717}&=\sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}(239k-233)^{717}
\end{align*}

Expanding $(239k-233)^{717}$ into binomial coefficients, we can write it as:

\begin{align*}
S = \sum_{k=0}^{717}(-1)^k\binom{717}{k}\sum_{r=0}^{717}\binom{717}{r}(239k)^r(-233)^{717-r}
\end{align*}

The (k-r)th term in the sum will contain a factor of $(239k)^r$ and $(-1)^k$, so the term with the largest power of 239 will be the one for which k=r. We only need to keep the term in which 239^m divides the rth term, where m is the largest integer satisfying this. If 2^m divides this term, it is necessary that 2^m divides the sum $(-1)^k\binom{717}{r}(239k)^r$, so we have that m is at least the largest integer such that 4 divides $\binom{717}{r}$. By Pascal's Identity, this is given by $\boxed{\text{m=7}}$.

ANSWER: 7
